The South African Reserve Bank has released the December 2022 Quarterly Bulletin ‚Äì an overview of domestic economic development in the third quarter of 2022. You can find the full QB here https://t.co/VGstoTZ7Xt or download mobile app - 
https://t.co/3LCVw2MWXI #SARBQBDEC22 https://t.co/B6hWkntA3F

You can find the full December 2022 Quarterly Bulletin here: https://t.co/VGstoUgIP1 or download the SARB mobile app - https://t.co/3LCVw34xPg - to access current and historical Quarterly Bulletin publications. #SARBQBDEC22

SA‚Äôs net borrowing of R21.8 bn (1.4% of GDP) in Q1 of 2022 decreased to R227.3 mil in Q2 as gross saving improved. However, for the first half of 2022 SA recorded net borrowing of R22.1 bn compared with net lending of R137.6 bn in the corresponding period of 2021. https://t.co/NV5bwQbiOS

The much larger decrease in the deficit on the services, income & current transfer account than the decrease in the trade surplus resulted in a narrowing of the deficit on the current account of SA‚Äôs balance of payments from R107 bn(1.6% ofGDP) in Q2 to R18.1 bn(0.3% ofGDP) in Q3 https://t.co/MIbTNtqKRh

South Africa‚Äôs trade surplus narrowed further from R252 billion in the second quarter of 2022 to R233 billion in the third quarter. This extended the narrowing of the trade surplus from a peak in the second quarter of 2021. #SARBQBDEC22 https://t.co/ANu9JrlUGa

The value of both SA‚Äôs exports & imports of goods increased to all-time highs in Q3 of 2022, with imports increasing at a faster pace (3.1%) than exports (1.8%) from Q2. The increase in the value of exports reflected higher volumes, while that of imports reflected higher prices.

Preliminary non-financial public sector borrowing requirement decreased by a substantial R55.3 bn YoY to R61.6 bn between April & September '22, resulting from a significantly smaller cash deficit of general government as revenue collections increased in almost all tax categories https://t.co/dhBv8zzXP9

Households‚Äô debt burden increased at a slower pace in Q3 of 2022 as most categories of credit extended to them moderated. A combination of higher debt levels and interest rates caused households‚Äô cost of servicing debt relative to disposable income to increase to 7.5% in Q3.

Similarly, core inflation, which excludes the impact of food & non-alcoholic beverages, fuel and electricity, breached the midpoint of inflation target in July 2022.#SARBQBDEC22 https://t.co/THVOO7gHLe
Most measures of underlying inflationary pressures accelerated gradually during 2022, surpassing the midpoint of the inflation target range. #SARBQBDEC22

Consumer food price inflation accelerated from 6.2% in Jan '22 to 12.3% in October. The upward pressure emanated mainly from higher prices of bread & cereals, meat & fish, as well as milk, cheese & eggs, which together account for about 77% of the total consumer food price basket https://t.co/ZswpLsahtt

Contrary to the rebound in real GDP, growth in real gross domestic expenditure (GDE) moderated slightly to 0.6% in Q3'22 from 0.8% in Q2, alongside a decrease in real final consumption expenditure by households & a slower pace of increase in real gross fixed capital formation. https://t.co/4Jz2TLMbV8

Electricity load-shedding increased from 9.7% of the time in 2015 to 33.4% of the time in 2022 (until the end of October). During Q3 of 2022, it reached an all-time high of 1 054 hours, or 47.7% of the time. This included 187 hours of stages 5 and 6 load-shedding. #SARBQBDEC22 https://t.co/iNtaRvaPOx

Real GDP increased strongly by 1.6% in Q3 of 2022, boosted by the agricultural & the finance, insurance, real estate and business services sector, following a decrease of 0.7% in the second quarter. It surpassed the 2019 levels, before the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic. https://t.co/9dk4XahXmW

SA Reserve Bank Governor @KganyagoLesetja delivered a public lecture at the Wits School of Governance. His address is titled, 'Keeping it Simple: Monetary policy, growth and jobs in South Africa.' Read full speech here: https://t.co/51qyB8E2u4

@KganyagoLesetja: Now that the global economy is recovering & inflation in many countries, including SA, is rising, we have learnt that we must not be tempted to loosen our grip on inflation, or fall behind our peers as rates are normalised ‚Äì the consequences would be too costly.

@KganyagoLesetja:We confronted COVID-19 with relatively low stable inflation & policy rate space. We were able to soften the damage of the crisis with the policy rate, while still protecting value of the rand. We were able to play our part in maintaining macroeconomic stability.

The best chance we have with monetary policy to get faster, more job-rich growth is to maintain our focus on price stability with flexible inflation targeting ‚àí a proven framework. This enables the SARB to help maintain a stable environment that is conducive to economic growth.
@KganyagoLesetja We have an unemployment problem that needs more credible solutions. Employment & growth are both limited by factors that are beyond the reach of the central bank‚Äôs toolset.

If these are the primary constraints to job creation defined by the literature, & monetary policy has no impact on them, then the claim that more expansionary policies will solve the unemployment problem is simply an empty promise, backed up by little more than ideology.

[Watch Now] SA Reserve Bank Governor @KganyagoLesetja delivering a public lecture at the Wits School of Governance. His address is titled, 'Keeping it Simple: Monetary policy, growth and jobs in South Africa.' Click here : https://t.co/mFqJySvkKI

@KganyagoLesetja First, inflation does not create jobs & second, on balance, expansionary policy prompts more inflation than growth or job creation. This tells us that SA‚Äôs Phillips curve is near-vertical at a low rate of positive economic growth.

Historical data tell us about Phillips curves. One is that as inflation rises, unemployment rates rise. This characterises the late '90s & into latter half of 2003. From 2003 to 2007, however, we see another correlation, where inflation falls & employment rise

@KganyagoLesetja: As we have noted many times in the past, the solutions to our unemployment problem lie well outside the realm of monetary policy, and in fact the failure to employ those solutions directly limits the positive contribution monetary policy can play.

@KganyagoLesetja: Our basic problem is that while growth creates jobs, inflation does not. Not only does this fatally challenge the belief many hold in the existence of usable Phillips curves, but it also limits what macroeconomic policy can achieve in terms of job creation.

@KganyagoLesetja The open question is whether sustained expansion in an environment of high debt levels & rising inflation could live up to the hopes of those that argue for a ‚Äòjobs‚Äô mandate for monetary policy. The short answer is ‚Äòno‚Äô, but let me explain why.

[Thread]@KganyagoLesetja: Today, I want to spend some time unpacking why it is useful for the SA Reserve Bank & most emerging economies generally, to target inflation, and why achieving that goal ensures that monetary policy includes economic growth and job creation

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: The mid-points of our inflation forecast range correspond to 65.2% at end-2022, 22.3% at end-2023 and 8.8% at end-2024.

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: The net credit utilization of SMEs in September 2022 was 1.5 times higher than the January-September period of 2021. In this period, the amount of SME loans and their share in banking sector loans reached a historically high level.
Kavcƒ±oƒülu: As of August, the share of investment and export loans in total commercial loans exceeded 28%, reaching the highest level of the last 20 years.
Kavcƒ±oƒülu: The number of people employed increased by 4.1 million people since the first quarter of 2020.

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: Machinery-equipment investments, one of the focus areas of our targeted loan policies and drivers of potential growth, have been on a strong rise recently, and have been increasing steadily since 2019Q4.

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: The GDP per capita based on purchasing power parity, which better reflects welfare gains and productivity, reveals that T√ºrkiye grew faster than high-income countries and diverged positively from upper middle-income countries after the pandemic.

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: Exports and machinery-equipment investments, which are among the most important cornerstones of T√ºrkiye's structural transformation, continue to contribute to annual growth at an accelerating pace.

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: Domestic economic activity has continued without interruption and in a sustainable manner despite major supply shocks. The growth rates in the Turkish economy during the last eight quarters have been above other growth periods.

Kavcƒ±oƒülu: Geopolitical risks arising from the Russia-Ukraine War cause inflation to rise and demand to weaken on a global scale, while also fueling expectations for a longer-than-anticipated rise in inflation rates.

$LWLG has never commercialized a single product and we don't think it ever will. The business is worthless, and it won't be long before the company returns to the penny-stock status it occupied its entire history before the meme-stock pump of 2021. (8/8)

$LWLG devotees hang on every PR and grand pronouncement made by the company and CEO Michael Lebby, almost never understanding the industry context in which the assertions are made, which renders them either irrelevant or meaningless. (7/8)

None of that has stopped Lightwave's fanatical fan base from advertising their delusions of grandeur in >100K posts on the InvestorsHub forums. As true believers, they've ignored mgmt's blatant promotionalism, a corporate narrative that makes no sense, and decades of failure 6/8
In other words, any polymer or device that $LWLG claims to have developed, built, and tested is just a one-off production that can't be replicated consistently. (5/8)

Worst of all, former $LWLG employees confirmed that Lightwave has no way to consistently and repeatably manufacture the underlying EO polymers due to the fraught nature of electrical poling, which is a critical process in the fabrication of the polymer. (4/8)

Lightwave's claims are not even impressive. The modulators it supposedly tested in its labs run at slower data speeds than what's commercially available, and the power consumption specs are irrelevant for modern transceivers using advanced DSP functionality. (3/8)

Lightwave says its electro-optic polymers and optical modulators will enable 2-3x faster internet speeds, but it's been saying that since it went public in 2007. In the meantime, optical transmission speeds have increased >20x and $LWLG has generated zero revenue. (2/8)

Other than local sales and ops, there‚Äôs not a lot of costs in local currency. What am I missing?

Semiconductors are priced in USD, which effectively means server and networking equipment and the associated depreciation are in USD. Energy commodities are traded in USD. The high cost engineers are mostly in the US and paid in USD. Not many costs are in local FX.

The view that AWS benefits from FX since it prices in USD but has opex in local currencies is misguided. The reason it‚Äôs priced in dollars is because the vast majority of costs are denominated in dollars. The biggest costs are data center equipment, energy, and engineers.

I‚Äôm not a fan of how competitive $ATUS footprint has been and will get to over the next few years. Still, there could be an opportunity for shareholders based on (a) business stabilization returning, (b) some growth due to HP edge-outs...    16/n

Over the next 3-4 years, revenue will be flat-to-down, EBITDA margins will have peaked in 2020, CapEx will rise by 50% each year vs. 2021, and FCFE will be around-or-below $1bn (compared to $1.9bn in 2020). Instead of repurchasing shares, $ATUS will de-lever their B/S    15/n
In late 2020, $ATUS tendered a $3bn share repurchase at $34.21/share. Now, the $3bn could buy the entire public float of ATUS stock. The timing of the share repurchases were very poor.   14/n

Given the increased competition, slowdown in broadband subs, pressure on broadband ARPU, $ATUS is on the defensive & needs to invest to stabilize market share. Unfortunately, share repurchases are off the table just at the time when the stock price is at all-time lows. 13/n

Since IPO from parent-Altice Europe, ATUS spent $7.8bn running a levered equity shrink financial model, repurchasing 39% of shares since mid-2018. The issue is hindsight being "20/20" ‚Äì the avg. price paid is ~$27/share compared to current stock price $11/share for $ATUS 12/n
The market wasn‚Äôt expecting this and the stock has plummeted, dropping 65% in the last year. $ATUS 11/n

Suddenlink is now seeing increased competition & combined with existing competition in the $VZ FiOS overlap, ATUS announced in Q4-21 they are aggressively accelerating their plans to cover 2/3rd of their 9.3m HP in fiber (FTTH). They are on the defensive. $ATUS 10/n

This fierce competition puts continual pressure on total $ATUS subscriber growth given this = 1/3rd of total ATUS HP, as well as ARPU pressure due to the promotions. Broadband revenue growth last Q =  3% versus low-mid teens % 2017-2020. 9/n

Each year $ATUS gains broadband subscribers in the Optimum "non-FiOS" and Suddenlink footprint, while either slightly gaining or losing subs in the $VZ FiOS footprint. The competitiveness doesn‚Äôt seem to slow down. It has ramped up further in 2021    8/n

$VZ has competed against Cablevision in this footprint for 15+ years and they notoriously ~split market share.  Yet, instead of allowing for both to enjoy high profitability, they compete with excessive promotions, discounts, content bundling for free, and gift cards. $ATUS 7/n
The problem with Cablevision (Optimum) is about 60-65% of their footprint overlaps with Verizon FiOS (VZ), or about 3m HP. $ATUS 6/n

Cablevision (Optimum) has ~5.3m HP in the NY area, such as Brooklyn, Long Island, Bronx, The Hamptons, Greenwich CT. At first glance the footprint demographics are appealing: very high density, ~80% of plant is aerial, median income is ~30% higher than U.S. average. $ATUS 5/n

This has allowed Suddenlink to grow broadband subscribers and charge higher prices without as much concern for losing too many subs. Broadband ARPU is $70-$75+ (~10% higher than Cablevision historically) and EBITDA margins are high-40% (compare to Cablevision low 40%). $ATUS 4/n

Suddenlink (Acq 2015) operates in Texas, LA, OK, AK, North Carolina, and other small pockets across the U.S. for a total of ~3.7m HP. Only about 20-25% of the footprint overlaps with fiber, and thus Suddenlink has enjoyed low competitive dynamics over the last 5+ years. $ATUS 3/n
Cablevision and Suddenlink are *very* different cable companies due to their footprints, demographics, and competitive dynamics. $ATUS 2/n
Altice U.S. ( $ATUS) was formed through the combination of two cable companies in 2015/2016 ‚Äì Suddenlink and Cablevision ‚Äì by then-parent co. Altice Europe N.V. (https://t.co/EKhcIwhkfa). 1/n

A low WALE tells a story about potentials: upcoming turnover costs, risks to income streams, but also maybe an opportunity to boost rents to market rates?

A high WALE means more stability, but if you're locked into lower rates that diminishes the value.
Another term for it is WALE - Weighted Average Lease Expiry - which I kinda like more. If you're gonna do acronyms, make them shorter! https://t.co/8G1dGvrCgO
You can get a bit more granular depending on the lease, but it's an easy way to understand time left on the lease....and upcoming vacancy. Something especially important in times of a recession.

Term I learned: WAULT - the weighted average unexpired lease term.

Add up all the contracted rental income til the lease(s) expire and then divide it by the contracted annual rate.

It's a high-level measure to quickly judge a property or portfolio to understand lease time left.

Trend 10: Action through Regulation
Growing Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) are intensifying from industry groups, investors, and government regulation.

Expect a lot of change to happen.

Trend 9: Climate Change's Impact

Weighing changes with rising temperatures including health risks, energy costs, power outages, droughts, etc will test the CRE sector. 

Building resilience will be a key theme with buildings >> water efficiency, solar, etc.

Trend 8: Infrastructure spending, baby

Federal investment into decaying infrastructure ($1 trillion Bipartisan Infrastructure Law signed in Nov 2021) will focus on transportation spending along with other areas like broadband internet access.

Trend 7: Sun Belt Opportunities

Sun Belt markets have seen years of economic/population growth, but issues are rearing their heads.

Markets are changing: Congestion, lower affordability, and proper infrastructure may pose challenges in these hot markets.

The big issue is valuation: Big write-downs might be needed for conversions.

It's one of the areas of appraising that I'm fascinated to learn more about.

Likely will be triggered by major lease rolls or debt maturity.

Trend 6: Higher Purpose Housing

A lot of older buildings will need to be repurposed. "Retrofit for the future" seems to be the line. 

Consensus seems: We have too many office/retail and not enough residential/industrial. 

There's TONS of opportunity with older buildings.

Top tier office is in demand...Here's what to look for:

High ceilings / natural light
Sustainable design/zero carbon footprint
Premium health/safety features like efficient HVAC systems that refresh air https://t.co/Iz7z3lchEw

Interestingly...hotels...demand is there for resorts/destination spaces....but convention and business hotels are floundering.

Office is facing a lot of buildings built in the 1980s and are becoming functionally obsolete. https://t.co/ArHlzlgA6x

So:
GOOD: Residential/Industrial

MORE SELECTIVE: Retail and office 

But this really depends on the market. E.G. office can be converted to MOB (medial office buildings) > which is a strong opportunity! 

Look below at what's happening: https://t.co/qYYwPSAhm0

Trend 5: #CRE demand is healthy, but selection criteria is high.

Demand is for strong fundamentals: #industrial and #multifamily top the list along with niche like student housing. 

(Did I use enough hashtags to appease the Twitter GODS?!)

Trend 4: A Tale of Two Much/Too Many
Affordability is low and undersupply of building is high. 

Labor shortages, materials, supply chain, oh my! And restrictive zoning/building codes, NIMBYism, and fear for the future are limiting building.

Interest rate increases factor in as these make bonds and other interest investments more appealing.

And everyone is UNCERTAIN. No one knows what the future holds....specially with rates. https://t.co/ItxMDx40Tl
Think San Francisco CBD and you get what I mean. https://t.co/gK1Wn2xKqj

Trend 3: Capital Moving to Sidelines

Institutional investors might be moving to other easier assets with more stable returns than RE > but the theme seems to be: Investor demand is here for all real estate - except for Central Business District (CBD).

E-Commerce has grown in the pandemic from 13 percent in 2019 to a peak of 20 percent during lockdown (This shocked me - I thought e-commerce was WAY higher).

There will be multibaggers among former highflyers.

Many have debt on the balance sheet and negative cash flow.

They will be valued as bankruptcy risks.

Some will go bankrupt, some won't.

Some won't because of massive dilution. Some won't for other reasons.

Find the latter.

A trend everyone is talking about may not be the trend to ride (too late).

A business idea everyone is gushing about may not be the idea to pursue (too competitive).

A stock everyone is pitching may not be the stock in which to invest (too expensive).

Stay away from the crowd.
Successful value investing is not about buying companies that screen cheaply. It's about imagining a future others do not because they are blinded by fear.
